quran[7]{c,v,t}:
  73,1,"O you enwrapped one,"
  73,2,"stand up{1}during the night except a little–",footnotes:1:‘Stand up’ denotes adoration of Allah in night prayers.
  73,3,"for half of it or reduce it a little"
  73,4,"or add to it, and chant the Recital{1}slowly and distinctly.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  73,5,"Indeed, We are about to cast upon you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>a heavy word."
  73,6,"The vigil of the night is indeed more <span class="h">intense{1}</span>and more upright for articulation.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu ‘Amr and Ibn ‘Amer read it as: “…is indeed more suitable and…”</span>
  73,7,"Indeed, in the daytime you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>have lengthy work to do."
  73,8,"So remember the Name of your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord and devote yourself to Him with<i class=""s"">(solemn) </i><span class=""h"">devotion.</span>"
  73,9,"<i class=""s"">(He is) </i><span class="h">the Lord{1}</span>of the East and the West; there is no god but He, so take Him as a Trustee.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu ‘Amr, Hafs and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…devotion— <sub><small>9</small></sub>9 the Lord of the East…”</span>
  73,10,"And endure patiently what they say, and withdraw from them politely."
